title: For Sale/Trade:  Rifle Owners/Shooters Wanted
postcontent:
Can you shoot 4 MOA rapid fire without a bipod or rest? Can you do it with a rack-grade rifle and surplus ammo? Can you do it with iron sights? Want to be a Rifleman instead of just a rifle owner/shooter? Join us for an Appleseed Rifle Marksmanship clinic, April 14-15 2012 in Williamsburg, KY.

Project Appleseed is an activity of The Revolutionary War Veterans Association, a 501(c)(3) all volunteer, non-partisan, non-profit organization, dedicated to teaching every American our shared heritage and history as well as traditional rifle marksmanship skills. 

Appleseed rifle marksmanship clinics are non-competitive, family-friendly, and open to all, from novice shooters to experts. There is a $5.00 per day charge for women, and a $2.50 per day charge for youth (under 21). Peace officers, active duty military, National Guard, reserve, disabled and elected officials shoot FREE as honored guests. For all others, the cost is only $70.00 for both days, or $45.00 for one day of instruction by some of the best rifle marksmanship instructors in the nation. Attend one day or both days. Politics are not discussed at Appleseed shoots, except for the politics of 1775. 

You may shoot anything from a .22 rimfire (the Ruger 10/22 and Marlin 795 are popular) to a centerfire such as an AR, AK, SKS, M1A or M1. You will shoot approximately 250 rounds per day as you try to qualify as a Rifleman (210 Points) on a modified version of the AQT (Army Qualification Test) course of fire.

The number of slots for each shoot is limited, so pre-registration is highly encouraged to make sure a spot on the line is reserved for you. 

Learn More, Find Directions and Register at:
http://www.appleseedinfo.org/search-states.php?filter=KY&statename=Kentucky

Our state Facebook page:
http://www.facebook.com/KentuckyRifleman

title: For Sale:  FREE EOTECH 511 with the purchase of an as new Surefire M500A AR15 forend light
postcontent:
I am selling my Surefire M500A light. The light is as new. It has the white led guide lights. I bought it, put it on my rifle and shot a few rounds through it. I loved the light, but prefer a forgrip so I took it off and stored it. It is in perfect condition. To make the deal a little sweeter, with the purchase I am going to include my used EOTech 511. The EOTech has minor wear, but works perfect. For the light alone I paid $550.00 and over $400.00 for the 511. 

No flakes and lowballers, leave a contact number if interested. 

Here are the specs from Surefire:
Specifications 

Output / Runtime 
MN10 Lamp 125 .0 lumens / 60 minutes 
MN11 225 .0 lumens / 20 minutes 
Bezel Diameter 1 .62 inches 
Weight w/Batteries 1 .40 pounds 
Batteries 3
123A
Description M500A
The SureFire M500A replaces the original handguards of your M4 or similar carbine. It features a 9-volt shock-isolated incandescent lamp with a 1.62" reflector suited to close- to medium-range applications, and two low-output navigation lights available in white, red, or blue. Primary beam output is 125 lumens for one-hour of runtime using an MN10 lamp assembly (included) or 225 lumens for 20 minutes using an MN11 lamp assembly (included). The M500A has three primary beam switches integrated into the forend: a constant-on rocker switch (left side), a momentary-on pressure pad switch (right side), and a system-disable rotary switch (rear of battery housing) that locks all lights in the OFF position to prevent accidental activation during covert operations, transport, or storage. The navigation lights are operated by a smaller momentary-on pressure pad switch (left side). Proven in combat, used by military and law-enforcement around the world. 

FITS: Most M4-style (short handguard) weapons 
Features 
•High-output incandescent lamp with mid-size reflector for close- to medium-range applications
•Secondary LED navigation lights available in WH (white), RD (red), and BL (blue) 
•Switches—Primary beam: momentary-on pressure pad, constant-on rocker, system-disable rotary. Navigation lights: momentary-on pressure pad
•Construction—High-strength aerospace aluminum with Mil-Spec anodizing; impact-resistant polymer; coated tempered window
•Weatherproof—O-ring and gasket sealed
•Includes high-energy 123A batteries with 10-year shelf life

title: For Sale:  Gen 3 Glock 23 in .40 S&W  Sweet Shooter
postcontent:
For Sale: Generation 3 Glock 23 in .40 S&W.  Glock considers this a "compact" handgun.  

Glock test-fired this gun on 10-30-11 and I bought it new in November. This Glock has approx. 800 rounds through it. It has performed flawlessly!  There are no imperfections--dings, marks, or scratches.  So far it has eaten up 200 Wichester White Box, 100 Tula Ammo, 250 Federal, 2 Winchester PDX-1, 50 Sellier and Bellot, 100 Remmington, and 50 PMC.  I was trying to find something it didn't like--couldn't do it!

For more info on the G23....see the expert, Hickok45!
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f2YI6XYSSsk

It comes with everything from the factory----plus extra items!

Mags:
-3 13rd standard capacity magazines (OEM Glock)
-1 15rd hi-capacity magazine (OEM Glock)
-1 22rd hi-capacity magazine (OEM Glock-- add $20 if you want this)

Other:
-1 magazine holster that holds 2 magazines (works great--polymer)
-Glock Range Bag - (small)- easily holds gun, 5 mags, and ammo

FYI--
With a Glock 23 you can buy a G32 barrel and shoot .357 sig without any modifications or new magazines! I've done it with a friends G23---super fun!

With a 40-9 conversion barrel and 9mm magazines you can shoot 9mm at the range for a cheaper ammo option.

With a .22 conversion kit from Advantage Arms--you can shoot .22LR all day for pennies! My friend also has this kit---works great and super fun!

This is one of the few guns out there that offers so many options!

Face to Face sale only--must be able to give copy of FOID and Driver's License.

I am selling this gun because my Dad has one exactly like it.....going to inherit it someday so I figured I might as well branch out a bit!

Best regards,

Jon
